Executive Summary

Sephora is a multinational omni-etailer of personal care and beauty products, that offeres over 300 brands in moree than 2,000 stores across the world and online. Through Sephoras online website, it allows an for a new channel that welcomes the beauty shopping experience for all no matter where they are. Their website can also be used by customers not only to shop, but as a way to explore brands, curate their own lists, and interact with products and other customers through reveiws and ratings. This online shopping experience created by Sephora encourages people to not only love products with just the tap of a button, but also see how different factors like rating and price might affect those values. The main focus of our exploration is to analyze Sephoras online website data to see how factors like sales, discounts, and product availability impact cutomer reviews and ratings. Our exploration into these relationships we aim to uncover how these factors influence consumer happiness and loayty. Through conducting our analysis we found something about sales and love on price and rating filler, also gained insights that - was the most important factor in the rating/love count of a product online and that there are tradeoffs(?) when trying to identify the key drivers of customer satisfaction. Ulitmately our finding will help Sephora optimize procing strategies, sales events, and inventory management to align with customer preferences.

Introduction

The goal of this analysis is to help Sephora gain insights on effective marking camppagns and hekp sephora optimize product launches and promotions. We decided to use the sephora online website since it was a website that we as consumers have enjoyed, but thoguht the use of an online channel an an interesting aspect to explore academically.

The data set we analyze cames from a kaggle dataset that was collected using web scraping methods like selenium and beautiful soup to collect data from the Sephora website, and the files can be accessed through Kaggle The dataset includes 9,169 products across multiple categories (e.g., skincare, makeup) with 21 attributes, such as:

Product Attributes: Brand name, price, value per unit, category. Customer Metrics: Ratings, number of reviews, love counts (favorites). Sales Metrics: Discounts and product availability.

Reserch Questions

How do sales, discounts, and product availability impact customer reviews and ratings on Sephoras website? How can these insights be leveraged to create effective marketing campaigns for new deals and product launches?

1. Data Preprocessing and Exploratory Data Analysis

To explore this dataset, we visualized the main variables of interest. Before we can do that though we had to preprocess our data by handling missing data. Our data has just over 9,000 rows with 21 attributes that we can look at. To find missing values, we checed fro any null values throughout the data. Though this search we found that our dataset was already clean and only had missing value, which we removed and didnt affect teh overall size of our data.

After completing the data cleaning process, we started to do some exporatory analysis. Our exploratory analysis allowed us to gain some initial insights into our data before we go further into our analysis. One of the first parts of our exploratory analysis was to look at the descriptive statistics of our key metrics which we defined as number_of_reviews, love, price, and value_price. We also did a few other sorts inorder to see how the count of the categories varried as well as the rating distributions.

We then made a few visualizations to see if we can see any intial relationships between attributes like rating and price. As well as some barchart to visualize the number of products the top brinds at Sephora has and the count of products that contain certain marketing flags. These initial visualizations - filler.

2. Segment Analysis

Using the following criteria, the segmentation analysis divided Sephora products into four groups:rating, number_of_reviews, love, price, and value_price. We used the Elbow Method to find the ideal number of clusters after cleaning the data by eliminating missing values. According to the elbow plot, four clusters would offer the most insightful segmentation.

Segment 1: This segment has moderately high ratings (4.11) and love counts (7,211), with a relatively high average price of $96.61 and moderate customer reviews (118.87). It represents premium products with steady engagement. Segment 2: Characterized by moderate ratings (3.96) but the highest love counts (14,285) and reviews (227.53), this segment has the lowest average price ($31.28), indicating affordable, high-engagement products. Segment 3: This segment performs the best with the highest ratings (4.32), love counts (251,579), and reviews (5,519), paired with a moderate price of $35.67. It represents the most popular and well-loved products. Segment 4: With the lowest ratings (3.93) and engagement metrics (4,504 love counts and 39 reviews), this segment has the highest price ($241.12), suggesting niche or luxury products with limited appeal.

Each of the four clusters was given to a product using the K-Means clustering algorithm. Before classifying the products according to their similarity, the algorithm normalized the chosen features to guarantee equal contribution. In order to gain a better understanding of each segments features, we subsequently computed the average metrics for each segment.

There are clear distinctions between the groups in the table. With reasonable cost ($35.67) and the greatest ratings (4.32), customer love (25,157), and reviews (5,519), Cluster 3 is clearly the best-performing group. Cluster 4, on the other hand, has the lowest involvement and ratings despite representing the priciest products. Clusters 1 and 2 are in the middle; Cluster 2 has reasonably priced, high-engagement products, while Cluster 1 has reasonably priced, consistently performing things.

These revelations lay the basis for additional research, especially on Cluster 3, which performs the best overall. In subsequent analyses, we will dive deeper into these groupings.

# Selecting relevant numerical features
clustering_data = data.select([
    "rating",
    "number_of_reviews",
    "love",
    "price",
    "value_price"
]).drop_nulls()

# Create a pipeline 
def create_pipeline(num_clusters, random_seed = 42):
    pipeline = Pipeline([
        ('scaler', StandardScaler()),
        ('kmeans', KMeans(n_clusters = num_clusters, random_state = random_seed))
    ])
    return pipeline

# Pipeline ofr kmeans
def calculate_totwithinss(data, k):  
    kmeans_pipeline = create_pipeline(k, random_seed = 10)
    kmeans_pipeline.fit(data.to_numpy())
    return kmeans_pipeline['kmeans'].inertia_

k_values = range(1, 10)
totwithinss_values = [calculate_totwithinss(clustering_data, k) for k in k_values]

# DataFrame for elbow method results
elbow_results = pl.DataFrame({
    'num_clusters': k_values,
    'tot_withinss': totwithinss_values
})

# Elbow Plot
elbow_plot = px.line(
    data_frame = elbow_results.to_pandas(),
    x = 'num_clusters',
    y = 'tot_withinss',
    markers = True,
    labels = {
        'num_clusters': 'Number of Clusters',
        'tot_withinss': 'Total Within-Cluster Sum of Squares'
    },
    title = 'Elbow Method for Optimal k'
)
elbow_plot.show()

# Choose the number of clusters based on the elbow plot
optimal_k = 4  

# Run K-means clustering
pipeline = create_pipeline(optimal_k)
pipeline.fit(clustering_data.to_numpy())

# Add cluster assignments to the Polars DataFrame
clustered_data = data.with_columns(
    pl.Series(
        name = "segment_number",
        values = pipeline['kmeans'].labels_ + 1  
    )
)

# Calculate mean metrics for each segment
segment_summary = clustered_data.group_by("segment_number").agg([
    pl.col("rating").mean().alias("mean_rating"),
    pl.col("love").mean().alias("mean_love"),
    pl.col("price").mean().alias("mean_price"),
    pl.col("value_price").mean().alias("mean_value_price"),
    pl.col("number_of_reviews").mean().alias("mean_number_of_reviews"),
    pl.col("segment_number").count().alias("n") 
])

# Visualize segment summaries
segment_summary = segment_summary.sort("segment_number")
print(segment_summary)
segment_plot = px.bar(
    segment_summary.to_pandas(),
    x = "segment_number",
    y = ["mean_rating", "mean_love", "mean_price", "mean_value_price", "mean_number_of_reviews"],
    barmode = 'group',
    title = 'Segment Analysis: Key Metrics',
    labels = {'value': 'Average Metric', 'segment_number': 'Segment Number'}
)
segment_plot.show()

3. Effect of Love and Price on Ratings

The analysis looks at how customer engagement and pricing affect product ratings on Sephoras website. The results show different trends for love (customer affection) and price:

Theres a noticeable positive correlation between the number of loves a product receives and its average rating. Products that get a lot of loves also tend to have higher ratings, as shown by the upward trend in the data. This suggests that when customers really like a product, theyre more likely to give it a good review. High love counts could reflect customer satisfaction and loyalty, showing how Sephora successfully connects with its audience.

On the other hand, the connection between price and ratings isnt as clear. The data shows that price doesnt seem to have much of an impact on how customers rate products. This suggests that customers care more about the products quality and performance than its price. For Sephora, this highlights the importance of maintaining great product quality at every price point to keep customers happy

# Preprocessing: Selecting relevant features and dropping missing values
effect_data = data.select(["rating", "love", "price"]).drop_nulls()
effect_data_pandas = effect_data.to_pandas()

# Train-Test Split
X = effect_data_pandas[["love", "price"]]
Y= effect_data_pandas["rating"]
X_train, X_test, Y_train, Y_test = train_test_split(X, Y, test_size = 0.2, random_state = 42)

# Linear Regression Model
model = LinearRegression()
model.fit(X_train, Y_train)

# Print Model Coefficients
print("\nLinear Regression Model:")
print(f"Intercept: {model.intercept_}")
print(f"Coefficients: Love = {model.coef_[0]}, Price = {model.coef_[1]}")

# Predict Ratings 
effect_data_pandas["predicted_rating"] = model.predict(X)

# Visualization: Scatter Plots with Manually Calculated Regression Lines

# Love vs. Rating
fig_love = px.scatter(
    effect_data_pandas,
    x = "love",
    y = "rating",
    title = "Effect of Love on Ratings",
    labels = {"love": "Love", "rating": "Rating"}
)
fig_love.add_scatter(
    x = effect_data_pandas["love"],
    y = effect_data_pandas["predicted_rating"],
    mode = "lines",
    name = "Regression Line"
)
fig_love.show()

# Price vs. Rating
fig_price = px.scatter(
    effect_data_pandas,
    x = "price",
    y = "rating",
    title = "Effect of Price on Ratings",
    labels = {"price": "Price", "rating": "Rating"}
)
fig_price.add_scatter(
    x = effect_data_pandas["price"],
    y = effect_data_pandas["predicted_rating"],
    mode = "lines",
    name = "Regression Line"
)
fig_price.show()

4. Promotional Impact Analysis

The analysis explores the impact of promotional typesOnline Only, Exclusive, and Limited Editionon customer engagement metrics such as the average number of loves and the average number of reviews on Sephoras website. The findings reveal distinct trends for each promotional category:

Exclusive products have the highest average number of loves and reviews, reflecting strong customer appreciation and engagement. ustomers appear to value the unique positioning of these products, as they are only able to get these products in Sephora, leading to both high affection and willingness to leave feedback. This makes exclusivity a particularly effective strategy for fostering deep customer connections.

Limited Edition products exhibit a moderate average number of loves and reviews. While these products generate some level of customer affection and engagement, they dont perform as strongly as Exclusive products. This suggests that while scarcity can create initial interest, it may need additional marketing support to sustain customer attention and drive reviews.

Online Only products have the lowest average number of loves and reviews. This suggests that customers might value being able to test the product in store and not blind buy only. While online exclusivity may attract a niche audience, it does not consistently foster strong emotional connections or encourage feedback. Sephora could enhance this strategy by emphasizing the unique value or benefits of online-only offerings to drive greater engagement.

# Select relevant columns and drop missing values
promo_data = data.select(["online_only", "exclusive", "limited_edition", "love", "number_of_reviews"]).drop_nulls()

# Calculate counts for promotional indicators
promo_counts = {
    "online_only_count": promo_data.filter(pl.col("online_only") == 1).height,
    "exclusive_count": promo_data.filter(pl.col("exclusive") == 1).height,
    "limited_edition_count": promo_data.filter(pl.col("limited_edition") == 1).height,
}

# Calculate average love and reviews for each promotional type
mean_love_online_only = promo_data.filter(pl.col("online_only") == 1)["love"].mean()
mean_reviews_online_only = promo_data.filter(pl.col("online_only") == 1)["number_of_reviews"].mean()

mean_love_exclusive = promo_data.filter(pl.col("exclusive") == 1)["love"].mean()
mean_reviews_exclusive = promo_data.filter(pl.col("exclusive") == 1)["number_of_reviews"].mean()

mean_love_limited_edition = promo_data.filter(pl.col("limited_edition") == 1)["love"].mean()
mean_reviews_limited_edition = promo_data.filter(pl.col("limited_edition") == 1)["number_of_reviews"].mean()

# Create a summary DataFrame
promo_summary = pl.DataFrame({

})

5. Recomendations

  1. Impact of Sales and Discounts: The segmentation research shows that products that are likely to provide perceived value are frequently associated with clusters that have better consumer interaction (e.g., higher love metrics). Sales and discounts are a major factor in improving this perception. Products in clusters with high involvement but comparatively low ratings (e.g., Cluster 1) could be strategically targeted by Sephora. Giving these products a discount could boost sales, enhance reviews, and raise ratings all around.
  2. Product Availability and Exclusivity: Customers frequently feel a feeling of urgency when they see limited-edition or exclusive products. Customers appear to favor exclusivity and distinctive offerings, as indicated by clusters with high average ratings and strong involvement (e.g., Cluster 3). In order to increase conversions, Sephora might utilize these information to highlight product availability in marketing efforts by emphasizing only a few left or exclusive online deal messaging.
  3. Marketing for New Launches: New product launches might benefit from the insights gained from customer reviews. Products in clusters like Cluster 3, which have a high number of reviews and good ratings, reflect what consumers already value. When launching new products, Sephora can concentrate on highlighting comparable qualities. Promoting high-quality ingredients, eco-friendliness, or long-lasting qualityqualities that are often commended in reviewsfor instance, might guarantee a successful launch.
  4. Customizing Promotions: Targeted promotional efforts may be beneficial for high-performing clusters, especially those with high customer love but few reviews (e.g., Cluster 4). Providing extra rewards, like extra loyalty points for reviews, may stimulate comments and raise the profile and legitimacy of the product.
  5. Improving Customer Engagement: Items with high ratings but low love scores (such as Cluster 2) suggest that there is potential for an emotional bond with the product or business. In order to establish trust, Sephora could profit from include client endorsements and success stories in their marketing campaigns.
